<DOC><DOCNO> AP881111-0160 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-11-88 1610EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-China-Wildlife     11-11 0226</FIRST><SECOND>AM-China-Wildlife,0232</SECOND><HEAD>New Law to Crack Down on Wildlife Poachers</HEAD><DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A new law will take effect March 1 in China toprotect endangered wildlife from poaching that involves even thestate's security personnel, a pro-Beijing newspaper reported Friday.   Frontier guards and armed police in some provinces have usedtheir weapons to wantonly hunt wildlife, the New Evening Post quotedan unidentified official from the Chinese Ministry of Forestry assaying.   Illegal hunting of more than 20 endangered species such as thegiant panda and golden monkey is getting worse, the report said, andthe new law will be designed to put a stop to it.   Other illegal activity such as smuggling wildlife products alsois on the rise, the report said, noting that 1,639 pounds of muskwas smuggled to Japan in the first four months of 1987. Since lastyear, three giant panda skins and three golden monkey skins weresmuggled into Hong Kong, the newspaper said.   Since 1986, authorities seized 251 red deer and elk that wereshot dead by hunters in Inner Mongolia. In Anhui province, more than30 Yangtze River crocodiles were poached.   Tigers and leopards in southern China were among other endangeredspecies bagged by hunters.   The newspaper did not provide details of the laws provisions orwhat penalties poachers would pay for hunting endangered species.</TEXT></DOC>